ly affected by labor unrest. This work places the politics of Chinese workers in comparative perspective and a remarkably comprehensive and nuanced picture of Chinese labor emerges from it, based on a wealth of primary materials. It joins the concerns of 'new labor history' for workers' culture and shopfloor conditions with a more conventional focus on strikes, unions, and political parties. As a result, the author is able to explore the linkage between social protest and state formation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- Asian. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476653140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766531/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles